<div class="about-overlay" id="aboutOverlay">
  <div class="about-panel">
    <button class="about-close" id="aboutClose">×</button>
    <h2>GLASSES BLINK</h2>
    <p class="meta">A Sound of Someone project by Ziya</p>

    <h3>Concept</h3>
    <p><em>Glasses Blink</em> turns the sound of glassware — the kind we hear every day, almost without noticing — into music. A toast at dinner, the chime of a glass set down on a counter, a fingertip tracing the rim of a wine goblet: tiny acoustic events most of us treat as background noise. The project asks what happens when we treat them as instruments instead.</p>
    <p>Four families of glass — wine, tumbler, champagne flute, and crystal goblet — each modeled with the actual inharmonic partials its real-world counterpart produces. Visitors can tap a glass for a single bell-like note, hold it down to ring it like a wet finger on a rim, sweep across the row for a glissando, or enter Tune mode and re-pour each glass to retune the whole instrument live.</p>
    <p>Every glass is tuned to a note in the C major pentatonic scale. Pentatonic was chosen deliberately: every combination of notes sounds harmonious, so anyone who visits the site can make music without knowing music theory.</p>

    <h3>Inspiration</h3>
    <p>The starting point was the <em>glass harmonica</em>, the 18th-century instrument invented by Benjamin Franklin in which rotating glass bowls of different sizes are played by touching wet fingers to their rims. Composers from Mozart to Saint-Saëns wrote for it — its tone was famously described as almost unsettlingly beautiful.</p>
    <p>I was also influenced by the kitchen — the sound of a glass set on a marble counter, the high ring of stemware in a dishwasher, the way a glass of water on a passenger-seat cup holder hums at exactly one pitch when the car hits a certain speed. Tones you could write a song with, if you noticed them.</p>

    <h3>How to play</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Tabs</strong>: switch between Wine / Tumbler / Flute / Crystal — each plays a different timbre.</li>
      <li><strong>Click</strong> a glass for a single tap.</li>
      <li><strong>Hold</strong> to sustain — like rubbing a wet finger around the rim.</li>
      <li><strong>Drag across</strong> the row while holding to play a glissando.</li>
      <li><strong>Keys A S D F G H J K</strong> map to the eight glasses.</li>
      <li><strong>Tune mode</strong>: drag a glass up or down to change its water level and pitch.</li>
      <li><strong>Record / Play Loop / Clear</strong>: capture a phrase and have the page play it back.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Reflection</h3>
    <p>What I didn't expect was how much the <em>silence between notes</em> mattered. With a long-decay sound, two notes played one second apart blur into a chord; played four seconds apart, they're two distinct events. A row of glasses turns out to be a surprisingly expressive instrument once you stop trying to play it like a piano and start treating it like punctuation.</p>
    <p>Adding multiple glass types changed what the site invited. Wine glasses tend toward slow, contemplative phrases. Tumblers are percussive — short, mellow thuds that work as a rhythm bed. Recording a tumbler ostinato underneath a slow crystal melody felt like discovering the project had a band.</p>

    <h3>Technical notes</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Sound</strong>: Web Audio API. Per-note inharmonic synthesis using 4–5 sine partials at glass-specific ratios; tap envelope uses exponential decay (1.8s tumbler → 6.5s crystal); sustain envelope adds vibrato (~5 Hz, ~5 cents) and a 0.6s release. A 2.4s algorithmic reverb adds room ambience.</li>
      <li><strong>Tuning</strong>: pitch is computed live from water level using <code>freq = 220 · 2^((100 − level) / 50)</code>.</li>
      <li><strong>Visuals</strong>: pure HTML/CSS, no images. Each glass family has its own silhouette and glow color.</li>
      <li><strong>Recording</strong> stores the glass family on each event so loops replay across the correct families.</li>
      <li>No external libraries — single self-contained HTML file.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
